Catalonia Reopens the Debate on Limiting Housing Purchases for Speculative Purposes: A Policy Shift with Potential National Impact

This article is for informational purposes only and does not constitute investment advice or a recommendation in any form.

The Government of Catalonia has reignited one of Spain’s most contentious housing debates: whether to restrict property purchases made for speculative purposes. The initiative, promoted by Comuns and Esquerra Republicana de Catalunya (ERC), seeks to curb the acquisition of homes in high-pressure areas when the buyer does not intend to use them as a primary residence. Although the proposal has not yet materialized into a formal bill, the Parliament of Catalonia has requested a legal report to assess its constitutional feasibility.

The discussion gained traction after Esther Capella, Catalonia’s Minister of Territory, confirmed that the regional government is examining legal mechanisms to contain price growth in highly stressed markets such as Barcelona, Girona, and the metropolitan area. Meanwhile, Salvador Illa, First Secretary of the Catalan Socialist Party (PSC), has called for “realism” and “legal certainty,” stressing that any measure must respect property rights and the free movement of capital within the European Union.

According to the National Statistics Institute (INE), housing prices in Catalonia rose 11.6% year-on-year in the second quarter of 2025, well above the national average of 7.2%. The increase is driven by a lack of available land and the return of foreign demand, which continues to account for a significant share of transactions in coastal areas. At the same time, the rental market remains under intense pressure: data from Idealista show that the average rent in Barcelona reached €23 per square meter in October 2025, up 11.5% year-on-year, marking a new all-time high.

Supporters of the proposal argue that speculative buying—particularly in tourist zones and rapidly growing urban districts—has distorted the market and made housing increasingly inaccessible for local residents. They claim the measure would help restore the social function of housing and reduce upward price pressure. Developers and business associations, however, warn that restricting investment could have the opposite effect, reducing supply, slowing new construction, and ultimately driving prices even higher.

The Association of Property Developers of Catalonia (APCE) maintains that private investment remains essential to financing new housing projects. Its president, Xavier Vilajoana, stated in Expansión that “if investors lose legal certainty, they will simply redirect their capital to other regions.” The APCE advocates for stronger public-private partnerships to boost affordable housing development and streamline urban planning processes, rather than discouraging capital inflows.

While the debate is local in scope, its implications could extend nationwide. Regions such as Madrid, the Balearic Islands, and the Canary Islands, where housing markets face similar pressures, are watching closely. International precedents offer mixed lessons: countries like Canada, New Zealand, and the Netherlands have implemented partial restrictions on purchases by non-residents or short-term investors, sometimes achieving temporary price moderation but often at the cost of reduced supply and lower construction activity.

Beyond ideological differences, there is broad agreement that Spain suffers from a structural housing deficit. The Bank of Spain estimates that between 200,000 and 250,000 new homes must be built annually to meet demand, far above the roughly 90,000 units currently delivered each year. Private and retail investment will therefore remain critical to bridging this gap. In this environment, real estate crowdfunding emerges as a middle ground between speculation and inaction: it channels capital into specific projects with greater transparency, oversight, and local economic impact.

